        "---\n",
        "title: \"Political Media Spend Patterns in FEC Data\"\n",
        "subtitle: \"Real campaign finance data, partitioned Parquet, executive-ready analysis\"\n",
        "date: 2026-06-13\n",
        "categories: [Media Spend, Real Public Data, Parquet, DuckDB]\n",
        "toc: true\n",
        "toc-depth: 3\n",
        "code-fold: true\n",
        "---\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.section-label}\n",
        "Media Spend Analysis · Real Public Data\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.tldr}\n",
        "**TL;DR** — Analyzed real political committee disbursements from FEC bulk data files —\n",
        "converting pipe-delimited text into a cycle/month-partitioned Parquet warehouse and\n",
        "surfacing channel-level spend patterns across election cycles. Demonstrates a complete\n",
        "ETL workflow on genuine public data, with attention to schema design, query performance,\n",
        "and stakeholder-ready output.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.callout-data}\n",
        "**Data source:** [FEC Bulk Data](https://www.fec.gov/data/browse-data/?tab=bulk-data) — operating expenditures and committee master files. Public domain, pipe-delimited. The full archive runs multi-GB; the fetch script (`data/fetch_fec.py`) pulls and joins the 2020/2022/2024 cycles, then writes the result as cycle/month-partitioned Parquet. The case study reads from there.\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Business Problem\n",
        "\n",
        "Political ad spend is one of the few areas where **real, granular media buying data is\n",
        "publicly available**. Federal political committees must disclose every disbursement,\n",
        "including ad buys, to the FEC. The bulk data files contain millions of records spanning\n",
        "decades.\n",
        "\n",
        "For a media measurement professional, this is gold, but the format is gnarly and very messy. Files are\n",
        "pipe-delimited, the schema is dense and described in a separate header file, encoding is\n",
        "latin-1 (older filings have non-UTF8 bytes), and the historical archive runs to many GB.\n",
        "\n",
        "The challenge: **build a workflow that turns this raw data into something a media analyst\n",
        "or executive can actually use**...and do it in a way that scales to the full archive.\n",
        "\n",
        "## The Approach\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.approach-grid}\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.step}\n",
        "::: {.step-num}\n",
        "1\n",
        ":::\n",
        "::: {.step-body}\n",
        "#### Parse the FEC format\n",
        "Pull the pipe-delimited bulk files from fec.gov, fetch the published header CSV for column names, and join the operating-expenditures records to the committee master so each disbursement is tagged with its committee name and type.\n",
        ":::\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.step}\n",
        "::: {.step-num}\n",
        "2\n",
        ":::\n",
        "::: {.step-body}\n",
        "#### Design a partition strategy\n",
        "Partition by election cycle (high-cardinality, queries naturally cycle-bounded) and month within cycle (mid-cardinality, supports time-series queries).\n",
        ":::\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.step}\n",
        "::: {.step-num}\n",
        "3\n",
        ":::\n",
        "::: {.step-body}\n",
        "#### Categorize disbursements\n",
        "Map free-text purpose descriptions to standardized spend categories (TV, digital, direct mail, etc.) using a deterministic rule-based classifier.\n",
        ":::\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "::: {.step}\n",
        "::: {.step-num}\n",
        "4\n",
        ":::\n",
        "::: {.step-body}\n",
        "#### Surface analytical patterns\n",
        "Aggregate to channel × cycle × committee-type level and produce executive-ready visualizations of spend allocation patterns.\n",
        ":::\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        ":::\n",
        "\n",
        "## Step 1: Load the FEC parquet cache\n",
        "\n",
        "The fetch script (`data/fetch_fec.py`) downloads the operating expenditures and\n",
        "committee master zips from `fec.gov`, joins them on committee ID, and writes the\n",
        "result to cycle/month-partitioned Parquet. We read from there."
      ],
      "id": "68323d95"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: load-fec-data\n",
        "#| code-summary: Load real FEC operating expenditures from Parquet cache\n",
        "\n",
        "from pathlib import Path\n",
        "import numpy as np\n",
        "import polars as pl\n",
        "import pandas as pd\n",
        "\n",
        "CACHE = Path(\"../data/cache/fec\")\n",
        "if not CACHE.exists() or not any(CACHE.rglob(\"*.parquet\")):\n",
        "    raise FileNotFoundError(\n",
        "        \"FEC cache not found. Run `python data/fetch_fec.py` from the project \"\n",
        "        \"root first (downloads ~1 GB across the 2020/2022/2024 cycles).\"\n",
        "    )\n",
        "\n",
        "oppexp_raw = (\n",
        "    pl.scan_parquet(str(CACHE / \"**/*.parquet\"), hive_partitioning=True)\n",
        "    .select([\n",
        "        \"cmte_id\", \"cmte_nm\", \"cmte_tp\",\n",
        "        \"name\", \"transaction_dt\", \"transaction_amt\",\n",
        "        \"purpose\", \"cycle\",\n",
        "    ])\n",
        "    .collect()\n",
        "    .to_pandas()\n",
        ")\n",
        "oppexp_raw[\"transaction_dt\"] = pd.to_datetime(oppexp_raw[\"transaction_dt\"])\n",
        "oppexp_raw[\"transaction_amt\"] = pd.to_numeric(oppexp_raw[\"transaction_amt\"], errors=\"coerce\")\n",
        "oppexp_raw[\"cycle\"] = pd.to_numeric(oppexp_raw[\"cycle\"], errors=\"coerce\").astype(\"Int64\")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"loaded {len(oppexp_raw):,} real expenditure records\")\n",
        "print(f\"cycles: {sorted(oppexp_raw['cycle'].unique())}\")\n",
        "print(f\"total spend: ${oppexp_raw['transaction_amt'].sum():,.0f}\")\n",
        "print(f\"\\nsample rows (FEC bulk format, post-join):\")\n",
        "print(oppexp_raw[['cmte_nm', 'name', 'transaction_dt', 'transaction_amt', 'purpose']]\n",
        "      .head().to_string(index=False))"
      ],
      "id": "load-fec-data",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Step 2: Categorize free-text spend purposes\n",
        "\n",
        "The FEC schema has a `purpose` field, but it's free-text entered by the committee\n",
        "treasurers with no standardization. Real FEC data has things like \"MEDIA,\" \"MEDIA BUY,\"\n",
        "\"TELEVISION ADS,\" and \"BROADCAST\" all meaning the same thing.\n",
        "\n",
        "A rule-based classifier handles this reliably without ML overhead:"
      ],
      "id": "c6256452"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: categorize-spend-cleaned\n",
        "#| code-summary: Rule-based spend categorization\n",
        "\n",
        "import re\n",
        "\n",
        "### categorization rules: (regex pattern, category)\n",
        "### Order matters — more specific rules first\n",
        "CATEGORY_RULES = [\n",
        "    (r'(?<![A-Z0-9])(?:TV|T\\.V\\.|T\\.V|TELEVISION|BROADCAST|CABLE|MEDIA\\s+BUY)(?![A-Z0-9])','TV/Broadcast'),\n",
        "    (r'(?<![A-Z0-9])(?:DIGITAL|ONLINE|SOCIAL\\s+MEDIA|WEBSITE|FACEBOOK|GOOGLE)(?![A-Z0-9])', 'Digital'),\n",
        "    (r'(?<![A-Z0-9])(?:DIRECT\\s+MAIL|POSTAGE|PRINTING|MAIL\\s+PRODUCTION)(?![A-Z0-9])', 'Direct Mail'),\n",
        "    (r'(?<![A-Z0-9])(?:POLLING|SURVEY|FOCUS\\s+GROUP|RESEARCH)(?![A-Z0-9])', 'Polling/Research'),\n",
        "    (r'(?<![A-Z0-9])CONSULT\\w*','Consulting'),\n",
        "    (r'(?<![A-Z0-9])(?:PAYROLL|SALARY|OFFICE|RENT|TRAVEL|EVENT)(?![A-Z0-9])','Operations')]\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "def categorize(text):\n",
        "    text = str(text).upper()\n",
        "\n",
        "    for pattern, category in CATEGORY_RULES:\n",
        "        if re.search(pattern, text):\n",
        "            return category\n",
        "\n",
        "    return 'Other'\n",
        "\n",
        "\n",
        "oppexp_raw['category'] = oppexp_raw['purpose'].fillna('').apply(categorize)\n",
        "\n",
        "## honest coverage numbers, the key results section reads these at render time\n",
        "rec_cov = (oppexp_raw['category'] != 'Other').mean() * 100\n",
        "named = oppexp_raw.loc[oppexp_raw['category'] != 'Other', 'transaction_amt'].sum()\n",
        "dol_cov = named / oppexp_raw['transaction_amt'].sum() * 100\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"category distribution across real FEC operating expenditures:\")\n",
        "print(oppexp_raw['category'].value_counts().to_string())\n",
        "print(f\"\\ncoverage: {rec_cov:.0f}% of records and {dol_cov:.0f}% of dollars get a named category\")\n",
        "\n",
        "print(\"\\n example purpose strings the classifier saw (sample of 5 per category):\")\n",
        "for cat in ['TV/Broadcast', 'Digital', 'Direct Mail']:\n",
        "    sample = (\n",
        "        oppexp_raw[oppexp_raw['category'] == cat]\n",
        "        ['purpose'].dropna().unique()[:5]\n",
        "    )\n",
        "    print(f\"  {cat:<15} -> {list(sample)}\")"
      ],
      "id": "categorize-spend-cleaned",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Step 3: The partitioned Parquet warehouse\n",
        "\n",
        "The right partitioning here is **cycle** (queries are almost always cycle-bounded) plus\n",
        "**month within cycle** (supports time-series analysis without too many tiny files). The\n",
        "fetch script already lays the cache out this way, let's quantify what we got."
      ],
      "id": "b22caf08"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: parquet-stats\n",
        "#| code-summary: Inspect the cycle/month-partitioned warehouse\n",
        "\n",
        "import os\n",
        "\n",
        "PARQUET_ROOT = CACHE\n",
        "all_files = [\n",
        "    os.path.join(dp, f)\n",
        "    for dp, _, files in os.walk(PARQUET_ROOT)\n",
        "    for f in files if f.endswith('.parquet')\n",
        "]\n",
        "total_size = sum(os.path.getsize(f) for f in all_files)\n",
        "\n",
        "## compare against the row-equivalent CSV size for the same data\n",
        "csv_path = '/tmp/fec_oppexp.csv'\n",
        "oppexp_raw.to_csv(csv_path, index=False)\n",
        "csv_size = os.path.getsize(csv_path)\n",
        "\n",
        "## key results reads this at render time too\n",
        "compression_ratio = csv_size / max(total_size, 1)\n",
        "\n",
        "print(f\"Parquet warehouse: {PARQUET_ROOT}\")\n",
        "print(f\"  partitions:     {len(all_files)} files (cycle × month)\")\n",
        "print(f\"  total size:     {total_size / 1024**2:.2f} MB\")\n",
        "print(f\"  csv equivalent: {csv_size / 1024**2:.2f} MB\")\n",
        "print(f\"  compression:    {compression_ratio:.1f}× smaller\")"
      ],
      "id": "parquet-stats",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "markdown",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "## Step 4: Query with DuckDB\n",
        "\n",
        "DuckDB on Parquet is the right tool here — full SQL, partition pruning, no infrastructure.\n",
        "Notice how queries that filter on `cycle` skip entire directories of files."
      ],
      "id": "21fa562b"
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: duckdb-queries\n",
        "#| code-summary: DuckDB analytical queries\n",
        "\n",
        "import duckdb\n",
        "\n",
        "### DuckDB's killer feature: register the in-memory pandas frame (which carries our derived `category` column) and query it as a SQL table. Same engine\n",
        "### pattern that scales to terabytes of partitioned Parquet — we just point it\n",
        "### at a different source here because the categorization layer is in pandas.\n",
        "con = duckdb.connect()\n",
        "con.register(\"oppexp\", oppexp_raw)\n",
        "\n",
        "channel_by_cycle = con.sql(\"\"\"\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        cycle,\n",
        "        category,\n",
        "        SUM(transaction_amt) AS total_spend,\n",
        "        COUNT(*) AS n_transactions,\n",
        "        AVG(transaction_amt) AS avg_transaction\n",
        "    FROM oppexp\n",
        "    GROUP BY cycle, category\n",
        "    ORDER BY cycle, total_spend DESC\n",
        "\"\"\").df()\n",
        "\n",
        "def fmt_currency(x):\n",
        "    return f\"${x:,.0f}\"\n",
        "\n",
        "display = channel_by_cycle.assign(\n",
        "    total_spend     = channel_by_cycle[\"total_spend\"].map(fmt_currency),\n",
        "    avg_transaction = channel_by_cycle[\"avg_transaction\"].map(fmt_currency),\n",
        "    n_transactions  = channel_by_cycle[\"n_transactions\"].map(lambda v: f\"{v:,}\"),\n",
        ")\n",
        "print(\"Channel spend by election cycle:\")\n",
        "print(display.to_string(index=False))"
      ],
      "id": "duckdb-queries",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
    {
      "cell_type": "code",
      "metadata": {},
      "source": [
        "#| label: top-vendors\n",
        "#| code-summary: Top vendors by category — the kind of question stakeholders ask\n",
        "\n",
        "## light entity resolution before ranking. raw FEC names split the same firm\n",
        "## into multiple rows: \"RWT PRODUCTION LLC\" vs \"RWT PRODUCTION, LLC\" vs\n",
        "## \"MEDIA BUYING & ANALYTICS\" vs \"MEDIA BUYING & ANALYTICS LLC\"\n",
        "### kill commas and periods, collapse space runs, drop trailing LLC / INC / etc,\n",
        "### then title case. has to happen BEFORE the group by so the dollars combine\n",
        "v = oppexp_raw['name'].fillna('').str.upper()\n",
        "v = (v.str.replace(r'[.,]', ' ', regex=True)\n",
        "      .str.replace(r'\\s+', ' ', regex=True)\n",
        "      .str.strip())\n",
        "v = v.str.replace(r'(?:\\s+(?:LLC|L L C|INC|LTD|LLP|CORP|CO|PC))+$', '', regex=True)\n",
        "oppexp_raw['vendor_clean'] = v.str.title()\n",
        "\n",
        "## re-register so duckdb sees the new column\n",
        "con.register(\"oppexp\", oppexp_raw)\n",
        "\n",
        "top_vendors = con.sql(\"\"\"\n",
        "    SELECT\n",
        "        category,\n",
        "        vendor_clean AS vendor,\n",
        "        SUM(transaction_amt) AS total_spend,\n",
        "        COUNT(*) AS n_transactions\n",
        "    FROM oppexp\n",
        "    WHERE category IN ('TV/Broadcast', 'Digital', 'Direct Mail')\n",
        "    GROUP BY category, vendor_clean\n",
        "    QUALIFY ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY category ORDER BY total_spend DESC) <= 3\n",
        "    ORDER BY category, total_spend DESC\n",
        "\"\"\").df()\n",
        "\n",
        "display_vendors = top_vendors.assign(\n",
        "    total_spend    = top_vendors[\"total_spend\"].map(fmt_currency),\n",
        "    n_transactions = top_vendors[\"n_transactions\"].map(lambda v: f\"{v:,}\"),\n",
        ")\n",
        "print(\"Top 3 vendors per major paid-media category:\")\n",
        "print(display_vendors.to_string(index=False))"
      ],
      "id": "top-vendors",
      "execution_count": null,
      "outputs": []
    },
